---  
Details

**Dense connective tissue** , also called **dense fibrous tissue** , is a type
of [connective tissue](/wiki/Connective_tissue "Connective tissue") with
fibers as its main [matrix](/wiki/Extracellular_matrix "Extracellular matrix")
element.[1] The fibers are mainly composed of [type I
collagen](/wiki/Type_I_collagen "Type I collagen"). Crowded between the
collagen fibers are rows of [fibroblasts](/wiki/Fibroblast "Fibroblast"),
fiber-forming cells, that generate the fibers. Dense connective tissue forms
strong, rope-like structures such as [tendons](/wiki/Tendon "Tendon") and
[ligaments](/wiki/Ligament "Ligament"). Tendons attach [skeletal
muscles](/wiki/Skeletal_muscle "Skeletal muscle") to [bones](/wiki/Bone
"Bone"); ligaments connect bones to bones at [joints](/wiki/Joint "Joint").
Ligaments are more stretchy and contain more [elastic
fibers](/wiki/Elastic_fiber "Elastic fiber") than tendons. Dense connective
tissue also make up the lower layers of the [skin](/wiki/Skin "Skin")
(dermis), where it is arranged in sheets.[2]
